    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! L1 regularization adds a penalty equivalent to the absolute value of the magnitude of the coefficients to the loss function. This tends to make coefficients shrunk towards zero, thus performing feature selection by pushing less important features' coefficients to exactly zero. L2 regularization adds a penalty equivalent to the square of the magnitude of the coefficients, leading to smaller but non-zero coefficients that helps smooth the model by preventing any one feature from dominating the prediction. While both L1 and L2 are useful techniques to prevent overfitting, choosing between them depends on the problem and desired outcomes.",
