    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh i see. so basically l1 is like a filter that actually deletes things, whereas l2 just makes them smaller? i'm having trouble visualizing why the math actually forces l1 to hit zero exactly while l2 just gets really close but stays there. could you explain the intuition behind that part?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely! Think of L1 regularization as a constraint that pushes a coefficient down to the closest point along the axis that represents that coefficient in the model's coefficient space. Due to its linear nature, this point is often on the same axis, which means that exactly zero is the nearest point; therefore, pushing the coefficients to zero will minimize the L1 penalty to its maximum. For L2 regularization, which follows the quadratic nature, injuring the square of a distance can tolerate a tiny detour - a small error away from the original coefficient, as compared to the limited straight path represented by L1. Thus, this quadratic slope of the penalty curve in relation to the coefficient space allows L2 to maintain a coefficient at a minimal non-zero value that is still close to zero but not exactly, thereby never leading to a complete elimination, unlike L1 could do when minimizing the loss plus the penalty. The mathematics underpinning it exploits these geometrical perspectives with cost functions and the optimization landscape.",
      "source": "target",
