      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, the geometry part a bit helps. i'm still trying to wrap my head around the practical side though. if i have a massive dataset with like hundreds of features and i know only a few are actually relevant, would you definitely go with L1? and how would the 'shape' of the penalty affect how the model treats those useless features compared to the important ones?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For datasets with a large number of features where only a few are truly informative for the prediction, L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, is indeed your likely choice. Its 'shape,' which in the L1 penalty's case is a staircase or linear function that goes up to infinity, favors coefficients being driven to zero. In contrast to L2, L1 does not merely shrink coefficients uniformly but discriminates between more and less important features by aiding in exact zero value for the less important features' coefficients. This means that L1 a la Lasso can provide a more parsimonious model with potentially better interpretability and could work well in high-dimensional settings - due to a phenomenon known as 'sparsity induction.' L1's penalties force selection, hence, variables with negligible or zero contributions to reducing the model's prediction error are identified and along with them, the corresponding coefficients are shrunk to zero, improving the generalizability on new unseen data by reducing the model's complexity.",
      "source": "target",
